  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Promoting decent work and education in the rice sector in Pakistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Together with the milling company Rice Partners Limited (RPL) and civil society partners Fazaldad and V&#xE9;rit&#xE9;, Mars Food has initiated this project to better understand and address working conditions in the basmati growing region in Punjab, Pakistan, with a focus on risk factors for child labour.This region is characterised by a multitude of social issues, such as child labour, poor enforcement of women&#x2019;s rights, labour conditions, but also water scarcity and vulnerability to climate change. Rice is an important crop, as Pakistan is one of the world&#x2019;s top 10 rice exporting countries. Over 70,000 farm labourers are involved in rice cultivation, of which a substantial number are women transplanters. Rice transplanting is a significant source of income for women in some regions in Pakistan.In this project, Mars, Rice Partners and Fazaldad aimed to improve the working conditions of the workers in the field, with the ultimate aim to combat child labour. Field research indicated that contributing factors to the risk of children working included poverty and the related need to increase family productivity. The lack of a safe space for children while their mothers work and the lack of access to educational opportunities also played a role.The project partners therefore aimed to ensure better working conditions, including better health care, better child care and better salaries for the rice transplanters. In addition, they wanted to offer children prospects on a different profession by emphasizing the importance of education among children and adults, facilitating access to vocational education.</narrative>
  </description>
